,Recommended,244430,16542633,"Posted: 19 June, 2015",all,ThePhantomSafetyPin,"I have been a Myst fan for almost ten years now - ever since I was a freshman in high school - and walking onto the Unity-created Myst Island in this re-remake of the remake of the original was just like coming home for me. My first thoughts upon first walking onto the new Myst Island in full 3D motion was a single word - ""Wow"". Granted, the graphics here aren't perfect either, and there's a lot of improvement that needs to be done - but from the original point-and-click classic to this is a huge leap forward. Simply breathtaking work has been done on this!On the game itself... Myst was considered the game that really cinched the idea of CD-ROM drives in computers. If it weren't for this classic game by Cyan (now Cyan Worlds), the concept of computer gaming might not have caught on as readily as it has. Myst sets the standard for point and click adventure puzzle games, and many of the puzzle adventure games we have today owe a great deal to it. It is a great puzzle game with tough challenges that will make you think in different ways, from spatial relations to simple addition, logical leaps to sound-based puzzles and even a maze or two. Despite its difficulty and brain-teasing nature, Myst greatly rewards exploration, not with pickups or special items, but with amazing graphical design and a relaxing atmosphere that makes the game ideal for playing as a way to unwind after a long, stressful day. I could literally watch the sun rise and set over Myst Island for hours, or listen to the frogsong in Channelwood for ages (pun not intended). The story is simple - a great wrong has happened in the family of a man named Atrus, and his two sons Sirrus and Achenar are the only sources you have on the issue. Atrus himself is AWOL, and the brothers refuse to speak to you unless you bring them pages for the books they are trapped in - and so begins the journey into a tale of intrigue, injustice, and a terrible secret...That said, this game is not for everyone. Those that are not fans of Hunt-The-Pixel puzzles or puzzle games in general will not find much to like here. Those who prefer action are not going to find it here. Those who have no interest in taking the time to apreciate the beauty of little details are not going to enjoy this game. But for those of you who like a good mental challenge, enjoy taking your time, and love puzzle games, this is a must-have. Seriously, every puzzle or point-and-click fan out there OWES it to themselves to obtain either this copy of the game or another copy of realMYST. Just start it up, put on some headphones, and immerse yourself in the beauty of the game's worlds. Newcomers to the series will find a lot to enjoy here - and old friends will find it a wonderful welcome back."
76561197977046086,Recommended,244430,32206275,Posted: 5 June,all,Pyri,"My First point & click game was Myst: Masterpiece Edition, played it back in 2002 or so. From what i remember of it, it had difficult, sometimes unintuitive puzzles, fairly frustrating movement but the story and world that captured my imagination.Fast forward to 2017 and realMyst: Masterpiece edition.This game is gorgeous and atmospheric, the day and night cycle is breathtaking. And the music and ambient sounds really immerse you in the world.I must have also matured enough to grock the puzzles, because while i did not remember any of them from before, they all made sense and are very logical as long as you pay attention to the world around you. What a difference 15 years make :).Finally both choices of movement work fantastic and really make the game a pleasure to play and navigate.This was a very chilled out and enjoyable 7 hours that i will always treasure as part of my gaming life. I can not recommend this version of the game highly enough.If you are a fan on the genre do yourself a favour and buy it, if you are just trying to dip your toes into point & click puzzle/adventure games this is a perfect first game to try."
,Recommended,244430,10914586,"Posted: 28 June, 2014",all,Soroc,"If you were a fan of the original or a new comer, the latest patches have made realMyst: Masterpiece Edition a gem to play again.  One thing to note as of 6/14 the achievements still do not work from what I can tell.  Developer Cyan has stated that they are still in testing and will update further whe they are ready for general public.  The game has classic point and click controls as well as wasd/mouse first person controls.  I personally used the classic controls and instead of shifting panes like it used to do many years ago, now you get a nice walking simulation to the next area of interest. This walk movement simulation can also be scaled faster or slower.  In classic Myst fashion the game is extremely hard with puzzles that stretch across the environments. You have to use memory, sounds, and quickness to complete many puzzles in this fantastic setting.  If you are looking for a new challenge or haven't visited the original myst since the 90's you will be in for a treat with some of the toughest puzzles in any adventure game."
,Recommended,244430,8993150,"Posted: 6 February, 2014",all,Joe Biden,"This is a cautious recommendation from someone who grew up with Myst. A lot of this will be similar to a review for realMyst's original release.This is just as awkward to control as realMyst was, and having to move the mouse to slide a Marker Switch up and down or move the flow controls in Channelwood from side to side is not an easy experience if you are using free movement.This game uses the same movie files from realMyst (the brothers' library videos are the same as the original release, other videos are newer and less-well-acted). Myst: Masterpiece Edition runs like garbage on modern systems--if it runs at all--but at least when you play that you believe that Atrus believes what he's saying and isn't just reciting old dialogue.Having the original gameplay images for Myst pop up when you press Shift (while not using free movement) is a nice touch, though if you are running this on a modern resolution you'll barely be able to see the images in the center of your screen.The sound is as great as it ever was, although just like with realMyst, this version of the game does not completely mute the music at appropriate times (as in the fore-chamber).The music itself is not changed from classic Myst and that's a huge point in this release's favor.I guess there's a flashlight now but having just finished the game I never used it. Not sure what the point of it is unless you're too lazy to turn the crank on the battery in Stoneship. I can't think of any other locations that are very dark and also have something worth seeing. I don't even know what button it is bound to. Probably F.At the end of the day, this is still Myst, and one of the first games to tell a deep story purely by observations of one's environment (Gone Home also does this very well). Modern systems don't have many other ways to play other releases of Myst without jumping through compatibility hoops so having this on Steam is cool---BUT the original release is on iOS in untouched, fully compatible glory.If you own realMyst, this game is 12 bucks instead of 18. Maybe that will help sway you."
