,Recommended,244430,33362569,Posted: 7 July,all,PCQGames,"Finally, my childhood demons are quelled.The ultimate frustrations of never getting off the island, of desperately flicking switches and pressing buttons with no success have been sated.realMyst includes some nice tweaks, but wisely has kept the game intact, even including the option to play with the original control scheme. Both the original and free roam can be a little clunky, but the game moves much more quickly.Now that I've finally beaten this game, I can safely say MYST remains probably one of the best adventure games ever made. The style, sound design, acting and puzzle integration are something you would think every adventure game designer would have picked up on. While Myst has a reputation for being cryptic and difficult, I contend that's nostalgia talking. Lack of inventory eliminates tedious item-hunting and the frustration of throwing things at the wall until something sticks. The structure of the game immerses the player in the puzzles/realms rewarding them by revealing more and more story, rather than having a linear plot be bottlenecked by puzzles as obstacles.I would also like to give the developers of realMyst on making the in game walkthroughs spoiler-preventative, though I rarely had to consult them, given the quality of game/puzzle design. Still a classic, still worth playing."
,Recommended,244430,12177628,"Posted: 21 September, 2014",all,Lincoln Balloon,"Oh god the nostalgia...the nostalgia man.Myst was one of the first games I ever played as a child.  It helped shape the future of adventure games, and became the definitive PC game of the early to mid '90s, only being outsold by the Sims as late as 2002.  Myst is a timeless tale of a mysterious island filled with books that transport you to new and fantastic locales.  Ever played a game where you point and click through different scenes?  Myst probably inspired it.It wasn't until the last few years or so before I realized just how much Myst really affected me as a gamer.  I believe that everyone's gamer identity is in part defined by the games you are first exposed to.  So it makes sense to me why I have such a love of atmosphere and immersion, because Myst had that in spades.  There's nothing quite like standing on the shores of the island, listening to the wind and the waves.The game is primarily puzzle based, and that's where most people take issue with Myst.  The puzzles are often complicated and convuluted.  This remake edition solves some of it, but there's still a lot of head scratching.  Myst operates by its own set of rules that you have to figure out as you go along.  The game doesn't have a tutorial, or a compass, or anything telling you where to go or what to do (although this edition comes with a hint guide in case you're truly lost).  It is really a game about exploration and discovery.  And believe me, solving a puzzle on your own is a fantastic sensation.realMyst: Masterpiece Edition may be a little pricey at nearly twenty bucks, but it all depends on your viewpoint.  For me, it was worth it.  For some just coming into the series, it might seem a little like price gouging.  But if you're interested, I highly recommend checking out this standout title from gaming's youth.  This new edition enhances the graphics and includes the free form movement from the original realMyst, making it (in my opinion) the definitive edition of Myst.  So whether you're just an old fan looking for a trip down nostalgia lane, or a new arrival, Myst welcomes you to an adventure of mystery.  Because, after all, perhaps the ending has not yet been written.EDIT: I neglected to mention in my original review that this version of the game is sometimes janky.  It's not optimized very well at times, which might just be due to the Unity engine itself, but I can't be sure.  In any case, it's something you should be aware of if you are thinking of buying it.  I never had slowdown so bad it made the game unplayable, but it did come close in the Selenitic age.  I still consider it the definitive modern edition of the game, but it is certainly not without its faults."
