76561197963252113,Recommended,244430,10104771,"Posted: 13 May, 2014",all,GravyGoat,"So...I gave this a ""yes"" vote mainly because there isn't a ""maybe"".  The orignal Myst was one of the all-time greats, but it has to be taken in the context of the time when it appeared.  21 years have passed since then and it certainly wouldn't do so well today, when people expect full 3D accelerated graphics, full motion video, etc.  realMyst is an attempt to remake the game with these expectations in mind, perhaps to introduce the game to a new audience, to draw back folks like me who played it when it was new, and of course, to make a few bucks.  By the way, this is the third time they've updated the game and re-released it (not counting ports of the original game to many platforms).So how well does it work?  Well, it's not great - pretty good maybe.  The 3D engine seems poorly optimized.  Even on decent hardware it runs slowly, especially with the graphics cranked up.  The controls are clumsy, especially the mouse-look functions.  For some reason the game is very dark - they added day/night cycles and it seems to be perpetually night, and indoor locations are often so dark as to be unplayable.  For this reason, a flashlight has been added to the game, which is a necessity most of the time, but it really takes away from the game's visuals to only be able to see well in the spotlight.On the other hand, everything from the original game is here, you can move around somewhat unrestricted compared to the static screens in the original game, and when the lights are on it looks pretty nice.  The story is somewhat timeless and still ""plays"" well today.Here are a few notes on what I had to do to make the game playable (on a system with a 3.4 Ghz core i7 processor, 16 gigs of ram and a Radeon HD 6970M graphics chipset with another gig of ram).1. Turn down the resolution2. Turn down some of the effects3. Learn to ALWAYS mouse-look with the right mouse button - you don't have to do this while walking, but you do have to do this while standing still, and switching back and forth between methods is too confusing4. Keep the flashlight on at all times except when the glare obscures something on the screen5. Press shift while walking to speed up - otherwise movement is very slowA couple of other notes - there are a ton of hint guides for this game.  Try not to use them.  It's not a long game, the puzzles are meant to be challenging, and if you buzz through it with a lot of hints it will definitely not be worth $18.  Some of the hint guides may even be wrong in some particulars (correction, ARE wrong in some particulars).  Look at everything.  READ everything.  Take notes.  Relax and play at an easy pace.  Despite being 21 years old, Myst still has a great story, some neat moments, some fun puzzles - it CAN be worth the $18."
