76561197982395611,Not Recommended,244430,25961004,"Posted: 9 October, 2016",all,aTeemoMushroom,"Myst was the very first game that I felt truly immersed in.  Twenty years ago, I completely lost myself in the graphics, soundtrack, and puzzles of the game.  For whatever reason, Myst recently came to mind, and I thought that it would be amazing if there were a modern, up-to-date version of the same game.The title, realMyst, is enticing and gives you the impression that it's been remastered for the modern era.  I was sorely disappointed.  The game gives the option of running a classic mode (where you click around the map and the images fade from one to another) and a modern version where you can use WASD and the mouse to explore the world as it was (probably) originally meant to be explored.Unfortunately, this does not work as a modern gamer would expect.  Instead of linking the camera to the movement of the mouse, you have to push the pointer to the edge of the screen in order to pan the camera in any particular direction.  It's truly mind-blowing that such an out-of-touch interface would exist in 2016.  What's worse is that I run a dual monitor setup, and since I have to push the pointer to the edge of the screen to look to the right, and my desktop extends to the right onto the second monitor, the game is completely unplayable.  Instead of looking right when I push my pointer to the edge of the screen (and it's absolutely ridiculous that any game in 2016 would work this way), my mouse floats off to the other monitor.I even tried Windows+P to duplicate the image to the second monitor, but since my monitors are different sizes, the game crashed because it was unable to mirror the image to both screens.If you're looking to relive the wonder and awe of the original Myst, you're better off playing the soundtrack on YouTube and imagining it in your head.  This game is unplayable for the modern gamer."
76561198020789373,Not Recommended,244430,8995891,"Posted: 6 February, 2014",all,Pow,"Ok. Where to start. I'm going to approach this in chronological order of mythorough dissapointment with this title. My first wave of frustration eminatedfrom the lack of an options menu right at the beginning. I like to set myresolution at least before starting a new game, so I had to watch the nice intro inan eye wrenching 1280x720, which was a little annoying but overall not a hugedeal. After spawning in the world a menu comes up and tells you that you have achoice between free roam and and classic mode, awesome. Naturally, I pick freeroam, because nostalgia's great and everything but classic mode really defeats thepurpose of playing a real time version of Myst. Walking around in free roam wasterribly confusing at first and didnt seem to make any sense, but what I figuredout is that if you're standing still you have to hold down the right mouse buttonto look. But you can look freely without doing that while moving. This is aterribly unintuitive control mechanic that makes free roam into a kind of mentalgymnastic constantly trying to remember to hold down the mouse button everytime you stop for half a second. It is the most pointlessy alien and baffling firstperson mechanic I've ever played. It's like Cyan has been sealed away in a glassdome for the last 20 years and essentially invented their own control mechanicbased on what they knew from developing the orginal Myst and didnt bother at allto take an example from literally any other well designed first person game. It'salso worth noting that when holding down the right mouse button, not only is ituncomfortable to hold it down while moving the mouse, the sensitivity isinexplicably lower which adds a new variable of unnessecary awkwardness intothis madman's equation. In line with my frustration with the controls is the factthat there seems to be mouse acceleration that cant be disabled. I personally viewmouse acceleration with the same burning hostility that I would normally reservefor someone who had just burned my house down and♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥on my dog. And Ican't be the only one who feels this way so it would be nice to have a littlecheckbox or something like all of the FPS's ever that have a mouse-accelerationfeature. You know, just a thought. Now, that that's out of the way let's talk aboutthe engine. I've never been overly impressed with the Unity engine, and personallywould not choose to develop in it myself, but I really want to believe it can beused more efficiently than this. The fan for my decent graphics card that can runCrysis 2 with no real problems was screaming at full speed after about 2 minutes.I don't know if Cyan develops their real time titles in house but theyve neverseemed to reflect a firm grasp on how to develop assets for a games engine.Theyve always seemed to approach it with the same technique you would use forproduction rendering, in the 90's no less, going completely off the chain withtexel density and poly count for example, yet making no use of masking orlayering or anything of the sort that a modern node based shader editor can do tohide atrociously tiling textures. Foliage density is unneseccarily higher than acrack head fresh out of rehab, and I noticed a couple instances of vertex normalsbeing softened when they clearly didnt need to be which is just plain sloppy. I alsohave a sneaking suspicion that they took some of the textures from the 2000version of realmyst and hastily ran them through crazy bump. I love the originalMyst. It is a masterpiece, but this just seems like a sloppy insult to the original,which is exactly what I thought of the original realMyst from 2000. I hate to saythis, because Myst is so close to my heart, but I cannot reccomend dropping 17dollars on this mess of a game. If you're going to remake a classic for a 20thanniversary, have the decency to do it right."
