,Not Recommended,244430,9878560,"Posted: 19 April, 2014",all,Caped Crusader,"I'm a fan of the Myst series going back to the original release and am even a proud backer of Obduction, the recent successful Kickstarter by Cyan, but I must confess I'm rather disappointed by this latest remastered version of their original blockbuster. Sure, the game replicates the fundamental details of Myst, but the new graphics are quite shoddy in my opinion. When the first edition of realMyst arrived many years ago, it genuinely pushed the limits of the 3D hardware available at the time. Initially it was heavily criticized for poor optimization, yet paired with the right hardware and with subsequent patches, looked quite excellent for its day. The presentation with realMyst: Masterpiece Edition, however, might have been passable 5 years ago, but it's distinctly behind the pack for what's acceptable today, even factoring in that Cyan is a sort of indie developer lately. Textures and other details are soft, while the lighting is harsh and unrealistic. Perhaps this approach was taken to make the title easily adaptable for portable devices and low-end systems. In any case, the dated and simple graphics don't warrant the cost on PC if you've already played any of the previous versions. It's also a shame in my opinion that Cyan continues to use their one mega-hit as a crutch, when perhaps their time might have been better spent creating a real-time 3D version of Riven or possibly remastering one or more of the other sequels. Given these results it might have been better still if they'd simply remastered the original game using pre-rendered graphics, but possibly at 2k or 4k resolution. It surely would be more impressive visually than what we have here. If nothing else it was lush graphics that consistently defined the Myst series. This rendition sadly fails to live up to that legacy."
