,Recommended,244430,14552468,"Posted: 19 February, 2015",all,Shirish,"tl;dr version: Highly recommended if you like adventure games and/or puzzles, and if you don't rage on non-major technical issues.--------------------------------Since I'm mostly used to point-and-click or modern adventure games, Myst was a new experience for me. It's a great concept- the player has to rely on visual and auditory observations to solve some large-scale puzzles, which are all completely logical and range in difficulty from easy to medium-hard (but I've played quite a lot of adventure games and am used to them; newcomers to adventure gaming may find the puzzles harder, but still doable). There is no pixel-hunting and no inventory system, which automatically dispenses with inventory item combination puzzles found in most adventure games.The developers suggest playing the game as if the players were actually present in the Myst universe, for a fully immersive experience and to better appreciate the story. Therefore I recommend playing Myst when you have quite a bit of spare time and are mentally relaxed. This is not the sort of game you'd want to play to take a break from your hectic activities or in the midst of a busy time to relieve stress. I made that mistake and my general attitude was just to plough through all the puzzles. Nevertheless, even though I didn't pay much attention to the story (or the environmental story-related clues), I found it fairly intriguing.The environments are simultaneously strange and beautiful, and have certain mystic feel to them (probably why the game is called Myst?). There are not a whole lot of things to interact with, which I think is very good, because that means there's very little noise in terms of puzzle-solving; most of the things the player can interact with are related to some puzzle or the other. The music and soundscapes are soothing and appropriate to the environments, especially in Rime age.Now for some technical issues- first of all, realMyst: Masterpiece Edition is a remastered edition (graphics/interface overhaul) of realMyst, which itself was a remastered edition of Myst. The masterpiece edition also has a free roam feature. In the previous versions, the player had to click on a place the go there and the field of view was quite limited, which may have been restrictive but was not necessarily a bad thing. However, mouse movement in free roam view is very clunky. There are no subtitles, which makes it hard to listen to the characters' monologues, and there are no options to adjust the music level. The graphics aren't -that- good and the game suffers from poor optimization.Still, I highly recommend it for adventure gaming or puzzle aficionados who don't mind the above-mentioned issues (plus RMME supports achievements and trading cards, and has additional puzzles to Myst or realMyst)."
,Recommended,244430,14560965,"Posted: 20 February, 2015",all,bnicolino,"That´s my first experience with Myst and I have enjoyed very much, great puzzles and a great plot (although very mysterious at first).Pros:Great puzzles and storyBeautyfull visuals (althoug not that impressive graphics, one must remember it´s a remastering/remake of a 90´s game)Great hints system that actually helps a lot whithout spoling the gameCons:♥♥♥♥♥♥ controls, no matter what method you choose.Sometimes too dark at night, spoiling the game and the visuals. There´s a flashlight but it doens´t help.Some bugs that made me have to reload the game and repeat complete sequences. Bugs in this kind of game really destroy your experience, since you wanna progress by yourself and sometimes you´re not sure if it´s a bug or you´re just not doing what you´re supposed to."
