,Recommended,244430,10821423,"Posted: 25 June, 2014",all,loner,"For those unfamiliar with the game, Myst is a classic first-person point-and-click puzzle game, originally released in 1993.Mystseries is set in an interesting universe where different worlds can be visited through specially-written books, and this is exactly what you'll be doing throughout the game. Each world has a unique theme and a set of puzzles to solve, but rather than puzzles being your typical logic minigames - they rely observation. Pulling random levers, pushing buttons and trying to figure out what they do is what Myst puzzles are all about. The game itself is actually very short and can be beaten in under an hour if you know what you're doing..realMyst: Masterpiece Editionis a faithful remake of the game. Not without flaws, but certainly worthy of a recommendation. Its new modern features and visual effects make the experience even more immersive, while doing a great job preserving the charm and aesthetic of the original game. Free-roam controls add complete freedom of movement, while classic control scheme can also be enabled at any time.The game doesn't always run well, and compared to some of the modern games of the same genre its visuals certainly lack consistency and polish. However compared to original Myst it looks and plays much better.-----------I previously criticized realMyst:ME for somewhat awkward controls, crashes, poor performance and visuals while better than the original - still not good enough to justify the low framerates even on a high-end machine. Thankfully, the 2.0 update brought improvements to all of those areas.- While the game still suffers from low framerates in some areas - reducing the visual quality does improve it significantly. This wasn't the case prior to the patch and the game would stutter even on low settings.- Model and texture quality is very inconsistent throughout the game. In some areas the game looks better than even modern AAA games, while in others the model and texture quality looks 15 years out of date. Prior to the patch though, the latter was a much more common occurence."
