76561198137793865,Recommended,244430,17625745,"Posted: 20 August, 2015",all,CatWithGlasses95,"Being a console gamer, I was mostly oblivious to PC games. Most of the computer games I've played were board games, Solitaire, ""push-the-block"" puzzle games, and Space Cadet Pinball. It wasn't until recent years, where I found out about the world of early PC games, particularly LucasArts point n' click adventures, such as the Monkey Island series, but chose to stick with my N64 and PS2. As I continued gaming, I became more and more accustomed to the newer generations, but as gaming morphed into a soulless machine spewing out nothing but meatheads in power-armor teabagging endless n00bs, boring brown enviroments, gun and ragdoll physics, etc, I started exploring the realms the more cerebral games of yore just to keep my interest in the hobby alive. One of the games in particular that peaked my interest in the adventure genre is, Myst.Myst is a graphic adventure game from 1993. The game thrived on the PC back then and was remade and ported several times on many systems, including the Playstation, Sega Saturn, the Jaguar CD of all things, and Nintendo DS & 3DS (Both are regarded as the worst ports of the game) I did prior research in the game and checked out a bunch of reviews. Almost all of them kept yapping about how they loved this game as a kid, all this nostalgia-gushing, how the reviewers kept kissing the game's♥♥♥♥♥ I kept thinking, ""Is there ANY reviewer sees this game for what it is, other than from childhood significance?"" I decided to give the game a shot on my PS3, via PSOne Classics. I played it and I hated it...at firstIn the game, you take the role of the stranger. Some random stumble-♥♥♥♥ who happens upon a book that transports him/her to the island of Myst. The Stranger is left with no choice, but to explore the island. The island holds a library, a rocket, an observatory, a cabin, and a power room. All of which contain puzzles for the Stranger to solve. These puzzles reveal four different books that transport the Stranger to different worlds, called ""Ages"". Upon entering the library, the Stranger finds two standalone books, the red and blue book. Both contain a message shrouded in static as both books have missing pages. The pages have been scattered through the different Ages located on Myst Island. The Stranger is now tasked to piece together why he/she is there by putting together the books and deciphering the messages.The main detractor of the game is the whole graphic adventure aspect. As soon as you start the game, it places you on a picture of the island, and a cursor. You start clicking around and realize your means of locomotion are through pointing and clicking, suffering screen-by-screen. I've been spoiled by 3D-games like Mario 64, Banjo-Kazooie, even first-person games like Perfect Dark. The screen-by-screen felt really strange and slow. It took time to get used to it and I eventually stopped noticing. As soon as I got used to it, I was in for a cerebral, and sometimes obtuse ride.The game averts several gaming mechanics. There is no combat system, no enemies to fight, no risk of dying, no time limit, and no hands to hold. Myst Island is your oyster! Also, be prepared to take notes. Seriously, you're going to have to write a whole bunch of stuff down. Many of the puzzles involve memorizing numbers, symbols, safe combinations, some of them are visual puzzles, some are auditory (One involves deciphering sounds to distinguish between north, south, east, and west) This isn't a game that you play, but one that you experience. It's solely about piecing together the story of how you got there and how you're supposed to leave.Myst is quite a unique experience. I'd liken it to those ""escape the Room"" puzzles, but on a much bigger scale. The puzzles are challenging, if not a bit obtuse, the settings look nice, given the old graphics (I'd recommend the Masterpiece Edition, an HD remastering) and story seems interesting, (Though, I'll have to play the other 4 to get the whole story). If you're tired of teabagging n00bs and wish to experience a game that involves your grey matter, rather than an itchy trigger finger, then step up and see what you've been missing."
,Recommended,244430,17631676,"Posted: 20 August, 2015",all,Del Mingus,"I never got to play Myst when it was originally released so it was nice to get the oppurtunity now. For a 20 year old game they've done a nice job of making it look good. This game just drops you onto Myst island with no hand holding advice about what to do. You need to explore and figure things out. I really liked the puzzles in this game. Theres no obscure ridiculous ones. They all felt intuitive and if you explore your surroundings enough you'll eventually figure out the solution. The game really does a great job of giving subtle hints and clues. ( Thats not to say i didn't need to google a hint every now and again).Good points:- Nice remastered graphics- The islands in the game make for a very memorable setting. They seem so unique and unusual that it fits the game perfectly- Brilliant puzzles that are intuitive enough that they dont frustrate.Bad points:- The free roam controls felt a bit fiddly when walking aboutOverall this is a great game that im glad i finally got to play. If you havent ever played this game it's worth picking up this edition. Also worth mentioning if your completely stuck on a puzzle, try the Myst guide on Universal Hints System instead of just googling the answers. It'll give you useful hints without spoiling the answer as solving the puzzles yourself, even with a hint or two, is more enjoyable then just getting the direct solution."
