76561198112625248,Recommended,244430,17186287,"Posted: 23 July, 2015",all,daniel_j_fraser,"I love MYST. It was one of the first games I ever played as a child. Came out 1993 and I played it a lot when I was between 5 - 8. I used to spend hours and hours trying to figure out the mysteries of the island with my brother and neighbour. A few years ago when realMyst came out I was super excited because my original copy of Myst no longer worked since my computer was too new. Alas, realMyst was plauged with crashes and didn't work on newer hardware/software. I thought this game may be forever lost to me as nothing but a very fond memory...constantly haunting me as the game I could never finish. (As a child I was only able to ever complete the mechanical world.) Then I found the remastered 2.0 version and it ran perfectly on my windows 8.1 and I finally got to relive and complete all those childhood memories. It is bittersweet in a way. The game was so fantastic in my memory and now that it is done the mystery that has haunted me my whole life is gone. I was however finally able to finish a task I set out to complete 20 year ago though and that felt great too. The remake is awesome. It stays true to the game while adding functionality. Also there is a little surpise at the end but I won't spoil that ;) If you haven't played MYST ever then for sure pick this up, even being 22 some odd years old it holds up fantastically if you have played it, there isn't really much new to keep you interested unless you are looking to run down memory lane...but this game is fantastic and will always haunt my dreams, and MYST will always be that perfect lonley island I will wander in my dreams.10/10 for max feels from a game thats hardly a GB big."
76561198047066936,Recommended,244430,17236108,"Posted: 26 July, 2015",all,Neb,"What to say about this version of Myst?  Apart from ""it's better than the 3DS version"" -First of all, unless you've literally never played any version of this game before, the puzzles are not going to surprise you because THEY ARE STILL EXACTLY THE SAME. You can literally dig out your old notes from twenty years ago and use them to get through to the endgame.  This is probably my only real complaint with the re-releases of Myst, at least as far as the gameplay is concerned; would it have been so hard to add a random element to the puzzles?  Or maybe change a couple of them a little?  (Well, okay, there's a new Rime age and all, but even that one has been recycled from the original RealMyst.)So I guess nostalgia rules in the realm of Myst... but the main appeal of this game has always been its appearance, and I'm happy to say that has improved.  This version updates the original RealMyst to bring it in line with what modern hardware can produce, and the full 3D movement makes navigating the islands much easier (Channelwood treetops, I'm loking at you).The Steam version brings Myst up to date with Achievements, because that's what the kids are into these days (okay, I had fun trying to get them all too).If you're into the quiet, cerebral and immersive type of game, why not go for the one that made itself a landmark and give this game a try?  If you're an old fan of the game, there won't be too much in the way of new content to bring you back, but you'll have already made up your mind on this game by now anyway!"
