,Recommended,244430,34574957,Posted: 29 August,all,Sirithre,"Let's be honest, if you're looking at this, you've most likely already played Myst and are looking for a nostalgia kick.That, it delivers. With improved graphics. Improved. Not great, not even good by today's standards. Just improved.The bonus age just gets 'tacked on' at the end and alludes to the sequel. Not especially creative, but a fun little addition.The 'free roam' actually makes the game more difficult in a sense, as you no longer have the rails focusing you on a specific section making it easier for you to overlook items.The day/night cycle just ended up being annoying, as night was obnoxiously difficult to see in, even with the flashlight.If you for some reason haven't played it and are just trying to figure out whether to get Myst, realMyst, Myst Masterpiece, or realMyst: Masterpiece... Well that alone should warn you that these are clearly remakes with the sole intention of getting additional money out of the series. Do what feels right for you. Or whichever is the cheapest/on sale. The story and puzzles are the same either way.That being said, it was still enjoyable, and I'd recommend it for anyone who has an active interest in the Myst story."
,Recommended,244430,34626303,Posted: 30 August,all,Rapture,"I remember seeing my dad playing Myst way back in the day. I picked this game up for the nostalgia, but instead I got one of my most satisfying gaming experiences to date. This game doesn't have any tutorial and doesn't hold your hand. You're dropped on an island and expected to slove puzzles. Finding the puzzles is as satisfying as sloving them. For many of the puzzles, there is no amount of trail and error that will slove them. Your actions must have purpose behind them. The puzzles are also quite varied as opposed to being build around a single mechanic. Not every puzzle is perfect, but I really felt like a had achieved something when I beat this game. A real gem; play this game."
76561198098975488,Recommended,244430,34967545,Posted: 15 September,all,Water_Samurai,"If you've never played Myst before, and love puzzle games, this is a classic. For longtime fans, especially those who never played the later releases; this is the definitive version to pick up. There is an additional Age to explore after beating the game, and while short, it adds a lot of depth to the characters that are here. Some of which I now feel should have been in the original game, considering how it connects to Riven.There is also a loving nod to Ti'ana, which if you've read the books, this is just such an awesome easter egg, and if you haven't read the books, I suggest you do if you love this series, as it is canon and written by the creators. Of course, you don't have to read those until after playing the game, as it will spoil some of the fun of discovering the island's mysteries on your own. Which brings me to the only real gripe I have....I've already played this game several times in my life, and I wish I could somehow forget all the solutions, and the game itself, only so I can experience it all again in the same way as I had many years ago. However, with the addition of Free Roam, it does feel fresh as I was able to explore the island a lot more freely than I ever have. Though, the free roam was a bit more clunky than I would have liked, it was still a nice touch.Those are my closing thoughts. Now I can only hope Riven gets a treatment like this at some point."
